Sponsor sought for Vietnam web site <br>
HOLLIS L. ENGLEY <br>
Gannett News Service                 <br>
     <br>
``Re: Vietnam -- Stories Since the War'' was intended as a short-lived experiment when it was first posted on the World Wide Web by the people at Public Broadcasting's non-fiction independent film showcase ``POV'' with a grant from PBS.<br><br>
Five months later, the site is running out of money, but not out of interest. It has become a digital home for men and women of all ages affected by the Vietnam War.<br><br>
``I don't want it to end, it's so rich,'' says Marc Weiss of ``POV.''<br><br>
But ``POV'' has other projects. A new website -- ``Hong Kong 1997: Lives in Transition'' (www. pbs . org/hongkong) -- was just posted, with a dozen Hong Kong e-mail diarists watching the impending takeover of the British colony by the Chinese.<br><br>
Meanwhile, Weiss is trying to find another place for the site or a sponsor to pay for its upkeep. The budget, he says, is complicated.<br><br>
``We're not-for-profit,'' he says. ``We're primarily grant-driven, though not 100 percent. The Vietnam site was begun with money from PBS Online. They gave us what for them was a pretty good chunk of money to both develop the site and actively maintain it for two months. That got us through the end of December. We knew going in that we would have to<br>
raise additional funds on our own.''<br><br>
Now, he says, ``We have a backup plan. We have at least one and possibly two other sites that already exist that are willing to take over the active dialogue if we are not able to raise the money. We have to make a decision probably in the next few weeks. We're going to keep it going at least through Memorial Day and we're committed to that.''<br><br>
